to the success of transitional justice and future political possibilities. Chakravarti takes up the issue from Adam Smith and Hannah Arendt, who famously understood both the dangers of anger in politics and the costs of its exclusion. Building on their perspectives, she argues that the expression and reception of anger reveal truths otherwise unavailable to us about the emerging political order, the obstacles to full civic participation, and indeed the limits—the frontiers—of political life altogether. Most important, anger and the development of skills needed to truly listen to it foster trust among citizens and recognition of shared dignity and worth. An urgent work of political philosophy in an era of continued revolution, Sing the Rage offers a clear understanding of one of our most volatile—and important—political responses.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAngerxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aAngerxPhilosophy. 0aJustice (Philosophy). 0aNuremberg War Crime Trials, Nuremberg, Germany, 1946-1949. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aanger, violence, rage, emotions, masculinity, justice, vengeance, revenge, retaliation, legal system, south african truth and reconciliation commission, protest, revolution, rebellion, activism, trauma, government, authoritarian state, dictator, discrimination, prejudice, politics, nonfiction, morality, apartheid, civil rights, mandela, race, affect theory, adam smith, hannah arendt, civic participation, community, nation, political philosophy, nuremberg war crime trials, eichmann adolf, trial, litigation, testimony, sympathy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022611998440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226120041423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/i